---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container">
      <a href="/use-cases" class="link text-sm">← Use-case playbooks</a>
      <span class="badge mt-6">Marketing stack playbook</span>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">Shopify marketing stack for {useCaseName}</h1>
      <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl text-cyan-100">{heroSubtitle}</p>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg text-slate-300">Trigger: {trigger} · Timing: {timing}</p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="container pb-12">
    <TldrBox title={`Stack picks for ${useCaseName}`} picks={tldrPicks} />
    <article class="prose-shopify mb-12 card">
      <h2>Stack execution playbook</h2>
  <p>Abandoned cart recovery on a full marketing stack is not a single automation checkbox — it is the highest-collision moment in your entire retention system. The shopper may have accepted a Privy popup offer, entered a welcome series, browsed three SKUs with Yotpo reviews loaded, and holds Marsello points — then abandons cart. Cart recovery only works when Sequenzy (or your lifecycle layer) reads all of that state before email one fires.</p>
  <p>Timing standard for most Shopify categories: email one at 1 hour with product proof and cart contents, email two at 24 hours with objection handling, SMS at 4 hours only if opted in and email one unopened, stop immediately on purchase. High-AOV stores delay incentive to email three; impulse low-AOV may compress timing but still respect offer caps.</p>
  <p>Variant inventory check is non-negotiable before any cart send. Fashion, beauty, and home goods stacks that email out-of-stock cart variants destroy trust faster than no email. Klaviyo and Sequenzy both need Shopify inventory sync at variant level — cart recovery pauses or swaps SKU when stock hits zero.</p>
  <p>Discount tiering by cart value prevents margin leaks. $35 cart and $350 cart should not receive identical 15% codes. Segment: under $50 modest or no incentive, $50–200 proof-first, $200+ education and financing before discount. Document max discount depth in collision calendar.</p>
  <p>Suppression rules define stack maturity. Cart recovery excludes: recent purchasers (7 days), active welcome series with same offer, wholesale/trade tags, employees, out-of-stock carts, VIP segments with pending personal outreach, gift registry edge cases, subscription first orders.</p>
  <p>Privy popup offer collision is the weekly failure mode. If popup delivered 10% and cart email offers 10%, shopper learns to abandon intentionally. Collision calendar row: popup code active → cart email one shows social proof only, no duplicate code.</p>
  <p>Postscript SMS after email silence — never parallel 15% on email and SMS same hour. One intent window, one offer maximum. TCPA quiet hours and opt-in status gate every text. SMS cart recovery justified when mobile purchase rate exceeds 40% for category.</p>
  <p>Yotpo proof in cart email one for consideration categories — installation photos for furniture, fit reviews for apparel, taste testimonials for food gifts. Proof before discount increases full-price recovery rate on email one measurably in A/B tests across verticals.</p>
  <p>Marsello loyalty points display only when enrolled and points balance &gt; 0 — showing empty loyalty module to first-time cart abandoners adds noise. Loyalty-earn reminder acceptable in email two for enrolled profiles only.</p>
  <p>Subscription and replenishment collision: active Recharge subscriber abandoning one-time add-on cart is valid recovery target; abandoning subscribed SKU they already receive monthly is not. Read subscription status before send.</p>
  <p>Analytics measure recovery rate, margin after discount, revenue per abandoned cart, SMS vs email recovery split, and incremental recovery on holdout cohort — not platform last-click alone. Finance reconciles recovered orders in Shopify weekly.</p>
  <p>BFCM week: tighten cart discount caps, extend SMS quiet hours, suppress cart for recent full-price purchasers, document VIP exclusions. Cart recovery volume spikes — deliverability and collision risk spike with it.</p>

      <h2>Merchant scenarios</h2>
  <p><strong>Fashion variant cart:</strong> Inventory check → Yotpo fit review in email one → related in-stock variant if primary OOS → Postscript at 4h if unopened → no discount email one.</p>
  <p><strong>Beauty replenishment cart:</strong> Subscription status check → routine reminder tone if replenishment SKU → exclude if active subscriber → modest incentive email two only for cold segment.</p>
  <p><strong>High-AOV sectional:</strong> Dimensions module email one → financing badge email two → 5% max email three for 7+ day consideration → Postscript only after 48h silence.</p>
  <p><strong>POD personalized cart:</strong> Personalized preview image email one → complete design CTA → 10% margin cap email two → no SMS unless high opt-in.</p>
  <p><strong>B2B trade account:</strong> Suppress consumer cart recovery entirely — route to rep notification in ActiveCampaign if cart value exceeds MOQ threshold.</p>
  <p><strong>Subscription box add-on:</strong> Recover one-time add-on only → suppress if abandoning duplicate of subscribed SKU → preview content not discount in email one.</p>

      <h2>Stack checklist</h2>
      <ul>
    <li>Variant inventory verified before every cart send</li>
    <li>Popup offer collision checked — no duplicate code email one</li>
    <li>Recent purchaser suppression 7 days active</li>
    <li>Welcome series overlap exclusion documented</li>
    <li>Wholesale/trade/employee tags excluded</li>
    <li>Cart value tier discount rules configured</li>
    <li>Yotpo proof block in email one for consideration categories</li>
    <li>SMS branch at 4h post-email-one if opt-in and unopened</li>
    <li>SMS quiet hours and frequency cap enforced</li>
    <li>Stop trigger on purchase within 1 hour</li>
    <li>Holdout 5% monthly for incrementality measurement</li>
    <li>Shopify reconciliation of recovered revenue weekly</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Exclusions (non-negotiable)</h3>
      <ul>
    <li>Recent purchasers</li>
    <li>Out-of-stock items in cart</li>
    <li>Customers in active support case</li>
    <li>VIP segments with better offers pending</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Metrics that prove quality</h3>
      <ul>
    <li>Recovery rate by cart value</li>
    <li>Margin after discount</li>
    <li>Revenue per abandoned cart</li>
    <li>SMS vs email recovery split</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Common mistakes</h3>
      <ul>
    <li>Same discount for $30 and $300 carts</li>
    <li>No inventory check before send</li>
    <li>Overlapping with welcome series</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Six-layer abandoned cart stack map</h2>
  <div>
    <h3>Capture offer state: Privy, Justuno</h3>
    <p>Know if popup offer already delivered before cart incentive fires.</p>
    <p>Cart email one suppresses duplicate discount if popup code redeemed or shown in session.</p>
    <p><strong>Failure mode:</strong> Popup 10% + cart 10% same session — trains intentional abandonment.</p>
    <p><strong>Operator test:</strong> Collision audit: zero duplicate offers same session last month.</p>
  </div>
  <div>
    <h3>Lifecycle execution: Sequenzy</h3>
    <p>Tiered cart emails, inventory gates, suppression orchestration, stop-on-purchase.</p>
    <p>Sequenzy owns timing, branches, and cross-layer suppressions.</p>
    <p><strong>Failure mode:</strong> Static 3-email discount escalation regardless of cart value or category.</p>
    <p><strong>Operator test:</strong> Recovery margin after discount — not just recovery rate.</p>
  </div>
  <div>
    <h3>Inventory and catalog: Klaviyo, Shopify</h3>
    <p>Variant stock check, dynamic cart contents, substitute SKU logic.</p>
    <p>OOS primary variant triggers alternate recommendation or pause.</p>
    <p><strong>Failure mode:</strong> Email shows abandoned SKU that is out of stock.</p>
    <p><strong>Operator test:</strong> Zero OOS cart emails sent last 30 days.</p>
  </div>
  <div>
    <h3>SMS urgency: Postscript, Omnisend</h3>
    <p>Single cart text after email silence with same offer cap rules.</p>
    <p>4h post-email-one if unopened; quiet hours; opt-in only.</p>
    <p><strong>Failure mode:</strong> SMS discount duplicates email discount same afternoon.</p>
    <p><strong>Operator test:</strong> SMS recovery margin positive vs SMS cost.</p>
  </div>
  <div>
    <h3>Proof layer: Yotpo</h3>
    <p>Social proof in email one before incentive layer.</p>
    <p>Category-matched UGC/reviews for cart SKU.</p>
    <p><strong>Failure mode:</strong> Discount-first cart with no trust assets on high-consideration SKU.</p>
    <p><strong>Operator test:</strong> Email one full-price recovery rate with proof block.</p>
  </div>
  <div>
    <h3>Analytics: Shopify, Klaviyo</h3>
    <p>Recovery rate, margin after discount, holdout incrementality, SMS split.</p>
    <p>Weekly finance reconciliation of recovered orders.</p>
    <p><strong>Failure mode:</strong> Platform-attributed recovery without margin context.</p>
    <p><strong>Operator test:</strong> Holdout cohort documented monthly.</p>
  </div>

      <h2>Timing and trigger governance</h2>
  <p>Email one: 1 hour post-abandon — proof and cart contents, no discount unless cold low-AOV segment policy.</p>
  <p>Email two: 24 hours — objection handling, loyalty state if enrolled, tiered incentive if policy allows.</p>
  <p>Email three: 48–72 hours — final incentive for discount-sensitive segment only; exclude full-price loyalists.</p>
  <p>SMS: 4 hours after email one if unopened and opted in — never before email one.</p>
  <p>Sale week: reduce max discount depth; extend suppressions for recent full-price buyers.</p>

      <h2>Measurement across the stack</h2>
  <p>Primary: recovery rate × margin after discount = recovery contribution.</p>
  <p>Secondary: email one recovery without incentive — proof path performance.</p>
  <p>SMS split: incremental recovery from SMS vs email-only holdout.</p>
  <p>Guardrail: intentional abandonment proxy — recovery rate spike with margin drop signals over-discounting.</p>

      <h2>Related playbooks</h2>
  <p>Upstream: <a class="link" href="/use-cases/browse-abandonment">browse abandonment</a> — suppress cart if browse flow active with conflicting offer.</p>
  <p>Governance: <a class="link" href="/use-cases/discount-strategy">discount strategy</a>, <a class="link" href="/guides/cross-channel-coordination">cross-channel coordination</a>.</p>
  <p>Vertical: <a class="link" href="/for/fashion">fashion</a>, <a class="link" href="/for/high-aov">high-AOV</a> cart variants.</p>

